103.body: When working with APIs in JavaScript, the fetch API provides a simple and modern way to make network requests. It allows us to retrieve resources asynchronously, typically in the form of JSON data from a server. The fetch function returns a Promise , meaning it works asynchronously and resolves with a Response object.
103.breadcrumbs: Fetch API introduction » Introduction to Fetch in JavaScript
103.title: Introduction to Fetch in JavaScript

104.body: Here’s a simple example of fetching data from a public API: fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1") .then((response) => response.json()) // Convert response to JSON .then((data) => console.log(data)) // Handle the data .catch((error) => console.error("Error:", error)); // Handle errors In the example above: We make a GET request to the API. We convert the response to JSON using .json(), which also returns a Promise. We log the result to the console. We handle any potential errors with .catch().
104.title: Basic Usage

105.body:
Using async/await makes the code easier to read and avoids deep nesting: async function fetchData() { try { const response = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1"); const data = await response.json(); console.log(data); } catch (error) { console.error("Error:", error); }
} fetchData(); :bulb: Unlike .then(), using async/await allows us to write asynchronous code in a synchronous style.
105.title: Using async/await

106.body:
The fetch API only rejects a Promise if there is a network failure (e.g., no internet connection). If the request is successful but returns an HTTP error (like 404 or 500), fetch does not reject the promise. To handle such cases, we need to check response.ok : async function fetchData() { try { const response = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1"); if (!response.ok) { throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}`); } const data = await response.json(); console.log(data); } catch (error) { console.error("Fetch error:", error); }
} fetchData(); :warning: Always check response.ok before processing the response. Your introduction to fetch is quite solid, but to ensure full coverage of the basics , I would suggest expanding it with the following additional topics:
106.title: Handling Errors

107.breadcrumbs: Fetch API introduction » Making Different Types of Requests (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
107.title: Making Different Types of Requests (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)

108.body:
The fetch API does not have a built-in timeout mechanism. If a request hangs indefinitely, you need to use the AbortController API. async function fetchWithTimeout(url, timeout = 5000) { const controller = new AbortController(); const signal = controller.signal; setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), timeout); try { const response = await fetch(url, { signal }); if (!response.ok) { throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}`); } const data = await response.json(); console.log(data); } catch (error) { if (error.name === "AbortError") { console.error("Request timed out"); } else { console.error("Fetch error:", error); } }
} fetchWithTimeout("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1", 3000); :warning: If the request takes longer than timeout, the request will be aborted.
108.breadcrumbs: Fetch API introduction » Handling Timeouts in fetch
108.title: Handling Timeouts in fetch

109.body:
Sometimes, you need to send additional headers in your request, such as an Authorization token. async function fetchWithHeaders() { try { const response = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1", { headers: { "Authorization": "Bearer YOUR_ACCESS_TOKEN", "Accept": "application/json", }, }); if (!response.ok) { throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}`); } const data = await response.json(); console.log(data); } catch (error) { console.error("Fetch error:", error); }
} fetchWithHeaders(); :bulb: Custom headers are required for authentication and setting request preferences.
109.breadcrumbs: Fetch API introduction » Setting Custom Headers
109.title: Setting Custom Headers

112.body:
To download and process binary data (e.g., images, PDFs), use Response.blob() : async function fetchImage() { const response = await fetch("https://via.placeholder.com/150"); const blob = await response.blob(); const imgUrl = URL.createObjectURL(blob); const img = document.createElement("img"); img.src = imgUrl; document.body.appendChild(img);
} fetchImage(); :bulb: blob() allows handling files, such as downloading PDFs or images.

113.body: Use Case Method Example Fetch JSON data GET fetch(url).then(res => res.json()) Send data to a server POST fetch(url, { method: "POST", body: JSON.stringify(data) }) Update data PUT fetch(url, { method: "PUT", body: JSON.stringify(data) }) Delete data DELETE fetch(url, { method: "DELETE" }) Handle errors Check response.ok if (!response.ok) throw new Error(response.status) Handle timeouts AbortController const controller = new AbortController(); Set custom headers headers fetch(url, { headers: { Authorization: "Bearer XYZ" } }) Send URL parameters URLSearchParams new URLSearchParams({ key: "value" }) Fetch binary data Response.blob() const blob = await response.blob();

Up until now, we were only able to check that the server is up and running. Let's now include our new products collection into the mix. Let's create a route /products which will accept the request method POST (as we want to send data to our API through this route). Let's now add the following code to our server.js file : import Product from './models/Product.js'; To import our newly created Product model from the file it resides in Let's now add the first route of our app (You can paste this code right under the statement app.use(express.json());: app.post("/products", async (req, res) => { const product = req.body // user will send this data if (!product) { return res.status(400).json({ success: false, message: "Please provide a request body" }); } if (!product.name || !product.price || !product.image) { return res.status(400).json({ success: false, message: "Please provide all fields" }); } const newProduct = new Product(product); try { await newProduct.save(); res.status(201).json({ success: true, data: newProduct }); } catch (error) { console.log("Error in Create Product:", error.message); res.status(500).json({ success: false, message: "Server Error" }); }
});

23.body:
:bulb: If you are used to testing your API routes, feel free to use the method you're the most used too. Don't switch methods because I showed you that one. The main goal is to make you a real full stack programmer, not to destroy the knowledge you've spent months (if not years) acquiring. As I'm more a CLI guy than a GUI guy, we'll use a utility called cURL to do so. Let's first prepare our data. At the root of the project, we'll create a directory called test_data. This is were our test JSON files will live. Let's now create a product file in this test_data directory (we'll reorganize the directory later on but for now it is enough). :bulb: If you are on Windows and can't create a file without an extension, you can give the extension .json to all the files we'll create in the test_data directory Here is an example of what our directory structure looks like so far : .
├── backend
│ ├── config
│ │ └── db.js
│ ├── models
│ │ └── Product.js
│ └── server.js
├── frontend
├── package-lock.json
├── package.json
└── test_data └── product 7 directories, 8 files Let's put the following data in our product (or product.js) file: { "name": "test_product", "price": 100, "image": "1234"
} This is a valid product definition which should be properly handled by our server. Let's now test this definition using the following command (from the root of our project) : curl --json @test_data/product localhost:5000/products You should see the following message: {"success":false,"message":"Please provide a request body"} Don't try to debug the command, it is working. The solution resides in the fact that we have to install the proper middleware to handle the JSON interpretation for us.

Let's now try to create a route that allows us to delete one product. We'll give this route the product id as a parameter . :bulb: If you open this documentation link, you'll have to ^f for (or cmd+f on mac) and search for Route parameters (case sensitive search) Let's add the following code to our server.js file (right after the app.post route): app.delete("/api/products/:id", async (req, res) => { const { id } = req.params; console.log(`id: \`${id}'`);
}); What it will do is allow us to give params to our requests to this route (in the req.params variable). We destructure the req.params.id into a variable named id and print it to the console.

27.body: Let's now write a cURL request that will allow us to test our newly created route. We can use the -X option to specify the HTTP Method we'd like to use. Thus leading us to the full request : curl -X DELETE localhost:5001/api/products/bonjour As you can see, even though the request was received by the server and the id: bonjour was printed, we can observe that the request hangs. This is because, by default, cURL doesn't have any timeout once connected (if the file is very large or the network very slow for example). To prevent our requests from hanging, we'll set a reasonnable timeout of 3 ms using the -m (or --max-time) option. Our full command is then: curl -X DELETE -m 3 localhost:5001/api/products/bonjour

Let's implement a route that will allow us to get all products. Let's add the following code fragment, right above the app.post route in our server.js file: app.get("/api/products", async (req, res) => { try { const products = await Product.find({}); res.status(200).json({ success: true, data: products }); } catch (error) { console.log("Error in fetching products:", error.message); res.status(500).json({ success: false, message: "Server Error" }); }
}); We give use the {} in the [.find()](https://mongoosejs.com/docs/api/model.html#Model.find(%29) function in order to retrieve all the products in the products collection.

31.body: Let's now add a few products to our database. You can either use a cURL request with different products or you can run it in a for loop (like the following if you're using bash): Once again, I'm a CLI guy so I suggest and use CLI tools, however if you're used to another method of working, feel free to do so with the method you've been acustomed to for i in {0..9}; do curl --json @test_data/product localhost:5000/api/products ; done You can see that this command added 10 products (the same though) to our database Let's now test our route. To do so, once again we can use our friend cURL to do the job for us. curl localhost:5000/api/products If you've been following the instructions in the terminal like I showed, you may have found that the output is not quite readable on its own. No worries, we can use another utility for that. It is called jq and is a great tool to work with json on itself, but for now we'll only use it to produce a more readble output from the cURL command. You can run : curl localhost:5000/api/products | jq to get a more readable output from the cURL command

32.body:
Let's implement the update of a product. Let's paste the following code in our server.js file. Somewhere near the other endpoints. app.put("/api/products/:id", async (req, res) => { const { id } = req.params; const product = req.body; try { const updatedProduct = await Product.findByIdAndUpdate(id, product, {new: true}); res.status(200).json({ success: true, message: updatedProduct }); } catch (error) { res.status(500).json({ success: false, message: "Server Error" }); }
}); We have just created a PUT route where a user can updated a product using the [findByIdAndUpdate](https://mongoosejs.com/docs/api/model.html#Model.findByIdAndUpdate(%29) mongoose method.
32.breadcrumbs: Express + MongoDB » Our last CRUD operation - updating a product state
32.title: Our last CRUD operation - updating a product state

33.body:
First let's get the id of one of our products. To do so, let's get all the products and pick the id of one product We can now test the route by running : curl -X PUT --json { "name": "Bonjour" } localhost:5001/api/products/<our_product_id> :bulb: Don't forget to replace <our_product_id> with a real product id We can now see that the request was successful. However, if the user enters a wrong id, we get a "Server Error", which isn't a very explicit message. Let's try and make it a bit more verbose. First, let's add the following import statement to our server.js near the other statements: import mongoose from 'mongoose'; And then let's add the following code fragment, right before the try..catch block in our app.put function: if (! mongoose.isValidObjectId(id)) { return res.status(404).json({ success: false, message: "Product not found" });
} What it does is that it uses the [isValidObjectId()](https://mongoosejs.com/docs/api/mongoose.html#Mongoose.prototype.isValidObjectId(%29) method of the mongoose module to check if the id can be used to construct an ObjectId variable Now, when we run our request with an invalid id, for example: curl -X PUT --json { "name": "Bonjour" } localhost:5001/api/products/1234 We now get the "Product not found" message.
33.title: Testing our route

Let's use vite tooling framework to setup our react application. We are going to run the following command: npm create vite@latest :bulb: Make sure that npm is installed on your machine. If you want, you can also use the Dockerfile provided with the project to build a custom development image. Build with : docker build -t node-dev . and run with : docker run -it --name dev-container -p 5173:5173 --mount type=bind,src="${PWD}",target=/app node-dev You can now name the project react-app, select React and then Typescript. Once the project is initialized, follow along and run : cd react-app
npm install
npm run dev npm install will basically install all the dependencies and npm run dev will run the dev script in package.json (which will start the vite server) You can now run curl localhost:5173 or visit localhost:5173 in your browser to ensure that everything is working. :bulb: If you started vite into a container, you might notice that the cURL request doesn't work. This is because you need to provide --host to vite in order to expose your server to your network (and not only to localhost). to fix this, add the --host option to your dev script in package.json.

96.body: In React, the useEffect hook allows you to handle side effects in your components. Side effects include: Fetching data from an API Subscribing to and unsubscribing from events Manipulating the DOM Setting up or cleaning up timers (e.g., setTimeout, setInterval) Before useEffect, handling side effects in function components was more complex, often requiring class-based components and lifecycle methods like componentDidMount and componentDidUpdate. However, with hooks, we can now perform side effects in function components in a much simpler way.
96.title: Introduction to useEffect

97.body: The useEffect hook takes two arguments : useEffect(effectFunction, dependencyArray); effectFunction : A function that contains the side effect code (e.g., fetching data, updating the title). dependencyArray (optional): An array of values that determine when the effect should run.
97.title: Basic Syntax

98.body:
If you don’t provide a dependency array, the effect runs after every render : import { useEffect, useState } from "react"; function ExampleComponent() { const [count, setCount] = useState(0); useEffect(() => { console.log("Effect ran after render"); }); return (

Count: {count}

); } export default ExampleComponent; :warning: Be careful when omitting the dependency array! If the effect runs on every render , it can lead to performance issues.
98.breadcrumbs: UseEffect » Running an Effect on Every Render
98.title: Running an Effect on Every Render

99.body:
If you pass an empty dependency array ([]) , the effect runs only once , when the component mounts : useEffect(() => { console.log("Component mounted!");
}, []); // Runs only once This is useful for fetching data from an API when a component loads.
